<TEXT>
the bush administration no longer is demanding 
that all farm subsidies that distort world trade be eliminated by 
the end of the century but critics question whether the change 
undermines an effort to boost us agricultural exports 
us negotiators on monday offered a compromise proposal aimed 
at breaking a deadlock that has threatened to scuttle a fouryear 
effort to reform the global trading system 
the administration said it would seek agreement from other 
countries to cut farm export subsidies by 90 percent and farm 
income supports by 75 percent over the next 10 years 
previously the united stateshad sought total elimination of 
tradedistorting agricultural subsidies by the year 2000 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter insisted that the 
administration remained committed to an ultimate goal of 
eliminating all such subsidies but felt the new proposal 
represented a good first step and would help to end a negotiating 
stalemate 
ninety percent reform is certifiably better than no reform and 
if this process fails we are going to have no reform yeutter 
told reporters monday 
but some critics questioned whether the united states by 
signaling a willingness to bargain on the percentage of subsidy 
elimination was opening the possibility that it will have to 
settle for a good deal less than even 90 percent 
they noted that the european community the 12nation trading 
bloc that is fighting the hardest to retain its subsidy program is 
considering offering a negotiating position to trim farm income 
supports by just 30 percent while leaving its export programs 
basically untouched 
sen max baucus dmont chairman of a senate finance 
subcommittee overseeing trade issues said the administrations 
latest offer embraced the dangerous concept of percentage 
reductions in agricultural support rather than insisting on total 
elimination 
since the european community already subsidizes its 
agricultural sector substantially more than does the united states 
a 75 percent reduction by both the united states and the ec would 
leave european farmers with a substantial advantage baucus said 
the fight over farm subsidies has threatened to scuttle an 
ambitious fouryear effort to overhaul the world trading system 
the talks being held under the auspices of the 97nation general 
agreement on tariffs and trade are due to conclude in 50 days with 
a marathon bargaining session in brussels 
president bush has made successful conclusion of the discussions 
his top trade priority but he has threatened to walk away if the 
united states does not prevail on the farm subsidy question 
the administration believes that the trade negotiation known as 
the uruguay round offers the best chance for boosting export sales 
by american farmers and businesses and thus reducing annual trade 
deficits that have topped 100 billion for six consecutive years 
agriculture is just one of 15 areas being negotiated the us 
team is pushing an ambitious agenda that also calls for dismantling 
barriers to trade in services a highgrowth area where american 
companies are extremely competitive and a crackdown on copyright 
piracy estimated to cost american companies 60 billion annually 
but agriculture is seen as the key to the talks because third 
world countries have balked at agreeing to us proposals on 
removing barriers to trade in services and strengthening copyright 
enforcement unless they win expanded markets for their farm 
products 
us trade representative carla hills said that in addition to 
the new proposal on agriculture the administration will unveil a 
proposal probably this week on changes needed to lift 
restrictions on access to markets 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

