<TEXT>
hampshire college the 
designyourowndegree school founded when the summer of love was 
still a warm memory turns 20 this year having survived the 
greedisgood 80s 
graduates and administrators of the school which still has no 
course credits grades or tenure say thats a testament to 
hampshires staying power 
we are certainly a long way from the 60s now said 
filmmaker ken burns a 1975 graduate whose civil war documentary 
recently won acclaim on public television 
when it opened hampshire was a bold experiment the brainchild 
of a group of educators from nearby smith amherst and mount 
holyoke colleges and the university of massachusetts its motto 
to know is not enough 
from its first class of 175 the school has grown to about 
1200 tuition meanwhile has grown from about 4800 in 1970 to 
more than 20000 
i think hampshires shown an enormous amount of courage in 
staying the course said 1977 graduate aaron lansky who credits 
the adventurous spirit of hampshire with helping inspire him to 
create the national yiddish book center now the worlds largest 
collection of yiddish works 
hampshire which has also produced nine oscar nominees and two 
winners has always had shock value with its coed dormitories 
gradeless classes and the story of the graduate who wrote his 
thesis on the aerodynamics of the frisbee 
graduates say it wasnt all freewheeling fun 
this whole thing of frisbee u and kind of the hippie school 
thing has gotten blown out of proportion burns said i never 
worked harder than i did at hampshire college in all my life 
at hampshire there are just passfail designations on a series 
of exams students must pass through three divisions in division 
i a student must demonstrate a rudimentary grasp of the concepts 
of the four schools of humanities and arts social science 
communications and cognitive science and natural science in 
division ii courses must be organized around a particular theme 
in division iii a student turns in a project equivalent to a 
thesis 
competition to get into those early classes was fierce 
there was a sense that we were making history that we had 
pioneered a whole new way of approaching education that wasnt 
based on processing individuals through a kind of assemblyline 
method of teaching said burns who has twice been nominated for 
an academy award for his documentaries 
hampshires slump came in the 1980s when applications dropped 
and concern grew that unqualified students were being admitted in 
response the student body was cut from 1200 to 900 and the school 
spent some of its 10 million endowment to operate 
perennial problems at hampshire are faculty overload from what 
amounts to a tutorial system of education attrition among students 
unable to cope with hampshires unorthodox ways and money the 
college depends on tuition and fees for much of its approximately 
25 million annual budget 
financial stability is one of the goals of president gregory 
prince who became hampshires fourth president in 1989 
recently after a nineday occupation of a dormitory in 1988 by 
students protesting what they perceived as indiference to minority 
issues students and teachers were required to incorporate a third 
world perspective into courses 
administrators say they wont relinquish hampshires 
experimental attitude 
for a college like hampshire what an anniversary like this 
helps underscore is how much time is on our side prince said 
