center for earthquake engineering research shook up a national 
quake conference two days before the anniversary of the oct 17 
1989 quake here 
the earthquake in the bay area last year is the writing on the 
wall for the east he told more than 300 scientists government 
officials and engineers this is a race against time and the 
odds of winning do not look favorable 
seismologists at the us geological survey estimate there is a 
64 percent probability of a quake measuring 60 on the richter 
scale occurring somewhere in the east within the next 30 years 
if that happens hundreds of thousands of apartment buildings 
are in danger of collapsing along with some bridges roads and 
railroad passes buckle said the result would be a huge number of 
deaths and injuries and tens of billions of dollars in damage he 
said 
new york city hit hard by a quake in 1884 could get some of 
the worst damage because of its poor soil in brooklyn and queens 
its dense population and thousands of older buildings of 
unreinforced masonry 
if the 1884 quake estimated at 59 on the richter scale much 
less severe than the 71 quake a year ago in the bay area were to 
occur again in new york it would cause 11 billion to 26 billion 
in damage buckle said a study has shown damage in the better 
prepared bay area was estimated at 6 billion 
and this is not thinking of fires because of broken water 
mains and the inability to control fires said buckle a 
professor of civil engineering at the state university of new york 
in buffalo 
skyscrapers built to withstand wind shear and long suspension 
bridges are less vulnerable he said 
mediumheight masonry buildings are common all along the 
atlantic seaboard where moderate and strong quakes have been 
recorded over the past 200 years charleston was struck by a quake 
estimated at 75 magnitude in the 1800s and boston had an estimated 
70 in the 1700s 
buckle said that because of a growing awareness of the 
earthquake hazard in the east some progress has been made 
massachusetts connecticut new jersey new york city and 
memphis tenn have adopted or are close to adopting seismic 
provisions in their building codes but he said that would affect 
only new structures 
the retrofit of critical existing structures and lifelines 
must be undertaken without delay he said 
in addition he said the dropandcover rules that california 
schoolchildren are taught should be taught to schoolchildren in new 
york and along the atlantic seaboard 
