department of ecology considers the proposal worth investigation 
he said the king has given assurances the tires would be burned 
only if the best pollution control technology were employed such 
technology is in use at a tire burning plant near modesto calif 
clark said 
tonga lives on tourism and banana exports as of 1983 the 
kingdom of 108000 people had 443 cars 
based on our plan to provide for future energy requirements as 
well as the present needs of tonga we would need a guaranteed 
supply of tires the king wrote 
in 1989 washington began collecting a 1 tax on every new tire 
for studies on tire disposal the fund has grown to about 2 
million but the department of ecology is still searching for ways 
to dispose of tires in an environmentally sound manner 
clark said some tires are chipped and used in highway asphalt 
others are made into truck floor mats tugboat bumpers and other 
products but the supply still overwhelms demand clark said and 
they pose a serious threat if they catch fire 
tire fires are extremely hard to fight and can burn for weeks 
their thick acrid smoke can make people sick and force 
evacuations 
an arsonist was blamed for a monthlong 1984 fire that burned 5 
million to 7 million tires in everett firefighters tried to douse 
the flames with water but the environmental protection agency made 
them stop saying the runoff was polluting a river nearby 
burning tires is an environmentally disastrous idea said 
joe thornton a toxics information specialist for greenpeace 
international in chicago 
tires are a complex stew of heavy metals chlorine and 
hydrocarbons the heavy metals arsenic lead mercury come out of 
the stack or wind up in the ash which becomes another disposal 
problem 
when burned toxic compounds such as cancercausing dioxin and 
pcbs are produced thornton said 
as has been amply demonstrated in this country the best 
technology is not good enough better equipment will not make the 
pollution problem go away he said 
let me ask you a simple question said ann leonard a 
spokeswoman for greenpeaces international waste trade project in 
washington dc 
if its environmentally safe to burn waste tires for energy 
why arent you doing it in washington ill tell you why because 
it isnt safe and people in your state wouldnt stand for it 
