was the site of one of several mouse creek indian villages that 
once dotted the banks of the tennessee river in southeast 
tennessee 
the first evidence of spanish contact at moccasin bend was found 
in 1915 by an archaeologist named clarence moore who spent a year 
digging at sites along the tennessee river between paducah ky 
and knoxville 
in the 1970s vandals and grave robbers seeking indian artifacts 
plundered the area across the river from chattanoogas business 
district leaving craters that still scar the site 
that prompted the creation of the anthropological association in 
1982 the group eventually found enough traces of pottery stone 
tools and arrow points to confirm the villages existence and 
configuration 
evidence shows hampton place contained a plaza houses trophy 
poles and a burial area all surrounded by a stockade well in view 
of the river mccollough said 
we knew even from the little bit that was known that it was a 
big and important historical complex that nobody had ever taken a 
serious look at or tried to define mccollough said 
