a private research group asked the internal 
revenue service on tuesday to investigate the taxexempt status of 
the national merit scholarship corp contending it discriminates 
against women and minorities 
the national center for fair amp open testing known as fairtest 
said only those students who are the highest scorers on the 
preliminary scholastic aptitude testnational merit scholarship 
qualifying test are eligible to compete for the prestigious and 
financiallyvaluable awards 
and it said those tests are biased against nonwhite and 
female students 
national merit officials said they were unaware of the letter 
and did not immediately respond further internal revenue service 
officials said the matter was confidential and refused to comment 
in a letter to irs commissioner fred t goldberg jr fairtest 
officials said the internal revenue service has previously 
determined that institutions which fail to follow racially 
nondiscriminatory policies are not to be considered charitable 
this policy requires among other things that schools not 
discriminate on the basis of race in their scholarship programs 
national merits exclusive reliance on scores from a biased 
exam violates this fundamental policy of nondiscrimination 
therefore national merit should not be subsidized by federal 
money through tax exemption said the letter 
fairtest a cambridge mass research organization estimated 
that minority students who make up a quarter of high school 
graduates receive a much smaller proportion of the national merit 
awards national merit declines to make public an ethnic breakdown 
of scholarship winners 
fairtest said it also has found that nearly twothirds of the 
semifinalists are boys 
thus rather than selecting from among the brightest and best 
collegebound students the program picks finalists from a pool 
of outstanding testtakers by eliminating 995 percent of all 
applicants solely on the basis of their score on a discriminatory 
test the organizations letter said 
talented women and minorities many at the top of their class 
are thereby eliminated from the competition by a single test score 
which even the testmakers say should never be used in isolation 
said the letter 
if the scholarship process were fair young women who receive 
better grades than young men in both high school and college and 
make up 54 percent of the qualifying test takers would earn at 
least that proportion of the awards or 44 million more than they 
currently receive said the letter 
it was signed by fairtest executive director cinthia schuman and 
by sarah stockwell the organizations university testing 
coordinator 
