state and local governments increased their 
tax revenues by 75 percent each in the 1989 fiscal year 
collecting 469 billion the census bureau reported on tuesday 
property taxes were the largest source 
state and local governments reported total revenues including 
taxes of 953 billion up 78 percent over 1988 when they were 
885 billion the 1989 revenues included 161 billion for a variety 
of services 126 billion from the federal government and 111 
billion from insurance trusts 
their spending in the 1989 fiscal year totaled 891 billion a 
78 percent increase including 263 billion for education 95 
billion for public welfare and 71 billion for governmentoperated 
utilities 
states collected 284 billion and local governments 185 billion 
in taxes the census bureau said in a preliminary report the total 
in 1988 was 436 billion the increase for 1989 was lower than the 
average for the previous five years when local taxes went up an 
average of 84 percent a year and state taxes 76 percent 
the bureau released some of the state figures in august and they 
showed that eight states had increases of more than 10 percent 
