expanding the powers of the securities and exchange commission to 
intervene during stock market emergencies and to monitor major wall 
street players 
bush said the measure would improve the stability of americas 
vital securities markets and the protection of tens of millions of 
investors 
the white house announced bushs action during a gop campaign 
stop in the chicago suburb of glen ellyn 
the measure will allow the commission to regulate program 
trading during times of extreme market turbulence program trading 
is the use of computers to execute scores even hundreds of 
separate trades all at once frequently in combination with trades 
in financial futures markets at the same time 
the bill also expands the authority of the sec chairman to shut 
down the securities markets with presidential permission in times 
of market emergency previously only the president could order a 
trading halt 
other provisions 
require large securities traders to report their market 
positions to the commission 
mandate coordinated clearance and settlement of stocks options 
and futures contracts between the sec and the commodity futures 
trading commission 
require the treasury department federal reserve board the 
cftc and sec to report annually to congress on their efforts to 
protect the integrity of the markets 
give the sec authority to assess the financial health of the 
parent holding companies of brokerdealers 
while hailing the bill bush said part of it was still 
troubling 
the final language of the bill gives the sec only carefully 
limited and narrow authority to control trading practices and is an 
improvement over earlier versions of the legislation bush said 
however it is still important that this authority be 
carefully and judiciously exercised to prevent any interference 
with technological innovations in financial markets that can 
enhance market liquidity the president added 
we must be careful not to damage the vitality of americas 
markets at the same time that we protect market stability 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

