<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachev today unveiled a new plan to 
rescue the soviet economy eliminating a 500day deadline for 
switching to a market system 
the 66page blueprint delivered to committees of the soviet 
legislature and signed by the soviet president is at least the 
fourth recent plan for reviving the economy 
it is the result of a threeweek behindthescenes effort by 
gorbachev and the countrys top economists to resolve fundamental 
differences over how to move away from a centrally planned system 
that fails to provide adequate food shelter or services for the 
countrys 285 million people 
peoples lives are becoming more difficult their interest in 
labor is falling their faith in the future is crumbling the 
plan says 
the plan which gorbachev is scheduled to present to the full 
542member supreme soviet on friday sets no time limit for 
switching to a market economy but states the experience of 
applying stabilization programs in other countries shows that 
such a period can take about 1 to two years 
it would give the soviet republics a powerful voice and new 
flexibility in running the countrys economy 
the main guidelines will determine only the principal 
approaches every republic moscow and leningrad have the right to 
act as they like within the framework of these guidelines 
gorbachevs spokesman vitaly ignatenko told reporters today 
the plan calls for establishment of an interrepublic economic 
committee to oversee reforms and for republic representatives to 
be included in central executive bodies ignatenko called the 
committee a departure from the tradition of ministries in moscow 
dictating to thousands of factories farms and businesses what to 
produce where to sell it and at what price 
in 1992 the plan says only the prices of bread meat dairy 
products and a few other staples would remain fixed by the state 
that is a slower transition to free pricing than envisioned in a 
draft prepared by soviet economist stanislav shatalin which 
envisoned a 500day deadline 
under gorbachevs plan republics would have the right to 
override price increases allowed by central authorities and to 
control most of the resources on their territory 
to reduce the huge amount of money that soviets have stashed 
away in personal savings the government would accept advance 
payment for scarce and expensive goods such as cars computers 
furniture telephones housing and rural plots the goods would be 
delivered when they became available and the government would not 
pay interest on the money in the interim 
shatalins plan received stong support from reformers such as 
boris yeltsin the president of the russian federation gorbachev 
earlier said he preferred elements of the shatalin plan to those in 
another proposal offered by prime minister nikolai i ryzhkov 
