<TEXT>
in a 1989 icelandic television 
documentary entitled survival in the high north icelanders 
talk about the difficulty of making a living on what they call 
the border of the habitable world 
a villager who hunted minke whales until a moratorium on 
commercial whaling says in apparent puzzlement it seems to be 
incredibly important to stop catching a few minke whales here every 
year but it doesnt seem so important to the world that it is 
being destroyed by nuclear pollution and that people are being 
killed all over the planet 
the villagers lament is heard often in a land where whaling has 
been a way of life for centuries this year for the first time 
since the 1940s iceland abandoned whaling part of a carefully 
plotted campaign to overturn the moratorium 
iceland one of the three major whaling nations along with 
norway and japan wants to kill whales again 
the whaling industry means to iceland what the auto industry 
means to the us said guthni bragasson spokesman for icelands 
foreign affairs ministry whaling is a small part of the overall 
economy but an important one but a more telling reason might be 
icelands very different point of view about the relationship 
between people and natural resources many people outside iceland 
view whales as magnificent creatures worthy of protection many 
icelanders view them as just another ocean resource 
when the moratorium on commercial whaling began in 1986 the aim 
was to give scientists time to determine whether they could set 
quotas that would allow whaling without endangering the mammals 
survival 
iceland immediately exploited a whaling commission loophole by 
beginning a program of scientific whaling arguing that it 
couldnt assess the status of its whale populations without killing 
and examining a number of whales 
that prompted greenpeace to launch a boycott of icelandic fish 
products picket lines appeared outside restaurants in the united 
