icelands population of 250000 spread thinly along the coast 
of a largely uninhabitable volcanic island the size of virginia 
has depended almost entirely on the sea for survival since the 
country was settled by norsemen and celts in the 9th century 
icelanders had been hunting whales for 600 years before herman 
melville chronicled capt ahabs fateful pursuit of moby dick in 
the 19th century an illustration in the 13th century icelandic 
book of law called the jonsbok shows a whale being flensed or 
having its blubber peeled off 
icelands fisheries now account for about 75 percent of its 
exports providing vital foreign exchange for a nation that must 
import nearly all of its manufactured goods before the whaling 
moratorium whale products made up about 2 percent of icelands 
exports sigurjonsson said 
iceland takes pride in its careful stewardship of its marine 
resources and that might be the one point on which iceland and 
greenpeace agree 
greenpeace has said repeatedly that iceland does have one of 
the bettermanaged fisheries in the world said sally shoup a 
greenpeace whale specialist in washington 
we want to have the responsibility for management of our 
resources because we are the party that will be hurt if the 
resources are overexploited sigurjonsson said people have 
been saying ok if we are not allowed to take care of the whales 
in our waters what will be next 
in 1916 icelands parliament the althing banned most whaling 
because of concerns about the depletion of whale stocks 
whaling resumed briefly in 1935 until it was interrupted by 
world war ii the present whaling operation began in 1948 in whale 
fjord a deep gorge on icelands eastern coast north of reykjavik 
the whaling station consists of a halfdozen redroofed yellow 
brick buildings on a hillside overlooking a broad concrete pier 
whales are hoisted up a wide metal ramp onto the pier where they 
are cut up and processed 
the station was nearly deserted during this summers whaling 
season the first summer since 1948 that the fjord hadnt resounded 
with the rumble of winches and cables and the shouts of whaling 
men 
the action this year was in the netherlands at the whaling 
commissions meeting there sigurjonsson and other icelandic 
officials argued that the whales they want to hunt are not 
endangered in icelandic waters 
the whales in question are fin whales sei whales and small 
whales called minke whales which are hunted by 50 or 60 families 
in iceland but not by the operation at the whaling station 
