a settlement between the state and 12 major 
automakers will provide up to 100 million in refunds to consumers 
under the states lemon law 
the settlement announced monday was believed to be the largest 
such refund ever by automakers and could set a precedent for other 
states officials said 
within the next month automakers will place advertisements 
detailing the details of the refund plan in major new york 
newspapers the ads will run for six weeks and consumers have 4 
months to respond 
the settlement covers all new york residents who bought or 
leased new cars after aug 2 1986 and who were forced to pay for 
repairs that should have been covered by warranty 
the repair must have been made after the manufacturers basic 
warranty expired normally duringthe first 12 months or 12000 
miles whichever came first but before the first 24 months or 
18000 miles or whichever came first 
the states lemon law requires manufacturers and their 
dealers to make repairs under their warranty at no cost to the 
customer for a period of two years or 18000 miles whichever 
comes first 
state attorney general robert abrams said monday that the 
settlement was the result of a longfought effort of four years 
to get the auto manufacturers to agree on the terms 
the car makers who entered into the agreement are chrysler 
ford general motors honda hyundai isuzu mazda mitsubishi 
nissan subaru toyota and volvo each company also paid the state 
10000 in costs for a total of 120000 but they did not admit 
wrongdoing in signing the settlement 
car makers such as mercedesbenz were not included in the 
settlement because their warranty programs are broader than the 
states lemon law abrams said 
