<TEXT>
federal officials have begun an 
investigation of the student loan marketing association office in 
lawrence kan to determine if it bought worthless loans to 
inflate assets and boost the companys stock price an fbi 
spokesman said 
max geiman spokesman in the fbis kansas city office said 
monday that agents with the education departments inspector 
generals office in kansas city and the fbi started a joint 
criminal investigation three weeks ago 
he said it began after two former employees filed a lawsuit 
alleging fraud within the loan servicing and purchasing procedures 
of the association commonly called sallie mae 
the purpose is to determine if there has in fact been any 
violation of any criminal laws geiman said 
he said the investigation could be lengthy given the complexity 
of sallie mae which holds 18 billion in student loans making it 
the nations largest purchaser of governmentbacked student loans 
the lawrence operation is one of five sallie mae loan servicing 
centers 
gisela vallandigham a spokesman at sallie maes headquarters in 
washington dc denied the allegations and declined to comment on 
the investigation 
geiman said the investigation is the result of the lawsuit filed 
in us district court in kansas city kan by diana crossfield 
and brenda albright former managers at sallie maes lawrence 
office 
ms crossfield was once the secondhighest ranking manager at 
the center she and ms albright allege they were forced to resign 
last year after telling top management about irregularities in 
sallie maes methods 
the two allege that sallie mae bought large numbers of void and 
canceled student loans from banks and employees were instructed to 
log those loans into the ledger even though the student borrowers 
clearly owed nothing 
they say that loans that had lost their federal guarantees were 
purchased and put on the books even though they stood to cost 
sallie mae money if the borrower defaulted 
further they contend sallie mae told students their accounts 
were delinquent when they were current in an attempt to collect 
more money 
their complaint does not indicate how large the problem was or 
whether the alleged practices were common outside the lawrence 
servicing center 
ms crossfield and ms albright said they discovered the 
problems during internal auditing ordered by management 
worried that recognition of those problems would result in lost 
revenue that would devalue sallie maes stock those supervisors 
allegedly stopped the investigation and forced out the two women 
besides sallie mae the lawsuit names nine individuals as 
defendants including edward fox and lawrence a hough the past 
and present presidents of sallie mae respectively 
the lawsuit alleges securities fraud as well as wire and mail 
fraud in a civil complaint brought under the racketeer influenced 
and corrupt organizations act the suit also alleges equal pay 
violations in which female supervisors were paid less than their 
male counterparts 
sallie mae denies allegations contained in the suit saying it 
has investigated the claims and finds no merit bankers who 
allegedly sold the bad paper also deny selling sallie mae void and 
canceled loans 
ms crossfield and ms albright filed suit for wrongful 
dismissal on sept 14 sallie mae has not responded to the 
complaint in court filings 
reports on the suit prompted federal investigators to approach 
the women for further information the two have declined to speak 
publicly about the allegations in their lawsuit 
student loans are guaranteed and subsidized by the federal 
government banks originate the loans but then sell them to a 
secondary lender such as sallie mae 
typically a bank sends a twoparty check to the students 
school before reselling the loan with the students signature on 
the check financial aid officers then cash them to pay tuition and 
fee if a student fails to enroll or doesnt qualify for the loan 
for some reason the loan is canceled 
</TEXT>
