european community nations remained divided 
tuesday over a subsidy reduction plan designed to end a deadlock 
with the united states in talks to liberalize world trade 
officials said the ec agriculture ministers could not back a 
compromise under which the ec commission would devise compensation 
measures aimed at offering a future to the communitys farmers 
sources said the compromise was rejected as too vague france 
and west germany were the strongest opponents to both the 
compromise and a 30 percent cut in subsidies while britain the 
member most favoring free trade supported the subsidy cuts 
the issue is key to the success of the uruguay round of talks to 
liberalize world trade held under the auspices of the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade the talks are scheduled to end in 
december 
the united states wants an elimination or drastic reduction in 
subsidies saying they give an unfair advantage to farmers in ec 
member nations but most ec states find as much as a 30 percent cut 
too drastic arguing the subsidies are needed to help their farmers 
compete 
the 30 percent cut would apply to such products as cereals 
rice sugar and livestock over the period 19861996 but not to 
subsidies for exports of ec farm goods 
on monday the ec missed a gatt deadline to submit a formal 
proposal on subsidies while the united states issued a proposal 
calling for 90 percent cuts in export subsidies and 75 percent cuts 
in subsidies to farmers over 10 years starting in 1991 
us agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said in washington 
monday the united states simply concluded that in the next 10 
years we may well not be able to get all the way 
but lets go as far as we can he added 
agricultural subsidies cost the industrialized world an 
estimated 250 billion a year with just over half of that spent by 
the ec 
